Park Grill's Rhode Island Calamari is to salivate for. Absolutely delicious! Some of my other favorites on the menu include the Crab Cake (Yum!), the King Pao Brussels Sprouts (Mmm!), the Greens and Grains (The salad lover in me can't get enough of these.), the Baked French Onion (I love French Onion soup, and this one is sinfully delicious.), the Carajilo, and the Double Espresso.  Equal to Park Grill's spectacular menu is its stunning interior (I could live in there!), its tony location, and its wonderful staff. I love this establishment. And of course, I would highly recommend it to those who have yet to relish its culinary offerings.  Five yummy stars.

We stopped here for dinner while visiting Chicago. Some of the reviews I see don't match our experience. I have to agree with that. I tried her mac and cheese and it was really good. My burger was excellent as well. Everyone gave their meal good reviews so I would certainly eat here again if I'm ever in the area.

Recently went to the Park Grill on an impromptu family trip to Millennium Park and ate outside in the plaza. We decided to pay a little bit more to eat in the park just to have a fun experience. We were seated right away at a rather tight table but we were in the shade so we were pleased. My 2 year old had a hot dog which I cannot review but looked more than adequate. My wife and I both got cheese burgers and they hit the spot and were decent. I personally really like the park sauce or whatever it was called. This all came with chips…out of a bag, which tasted fine but at $15/burger, let’s get real. However, I will rave about excellent Lemonade (I wasn’t in the mood for a beer though it looked like a good value.) 2 burgers we added cheese and bacon to and my son’s hot dog and my lemonade came out over $50 when it was all said and done.  When we go back to Millennium Park, we will be stopping in the Café at the south end of the building (There is Inside, The Plaza, and then The Cafe.) Small family friendly menu and prices and they have a couple tables to eat outside. We would have saved a lot of time and money and had the exact same experience since we were just looking for a meal so we could go enjoy Millennium and Maggie Daley Park.

Yes, we did speak to the manager and he was talking to the waitress when we left, but, I don't think I will ever go back. #CityExperts @GoogleLocalCHI  here's an update: Had a really bad experience with a waitress a few years ago here and I vowed to never go back here.  However,  we were invited to a private party here and decided to check it out again.  The restaurant has both Booth seating as well as table seating,  I would wait for a booth as they are larger and more comfortable.  We nibbled on a simple salad,  mini burgers, chicken sandwiches, and sweet potatoe French fries.  All were better than your average Party food.  With prices such as $18 for a hamburger, or a chicken sandwich for $14 with a side or salad,  prices are bit on the high side and there are lots of lower priced alternatives for food across the street on Michigan avenue.  They do have an extensive wine list,  as well as cocktails from the bar at premium prices.  I think perhaps the best feature of this restaurant is the location.  With gorgeous views of cloud gate (the bean), the ice skating rink (in winter) and our breathtaking Chicago skyline,  it is well worth a visit for the views alone.
